  "prompt": "What do the vacuoles in animal cells do?",
  "response": "In animal cells, vacuoles play several important roles, although they are generally smaller and less prominent than those in plant cells. Here are some of their primary functions:\n\n1. **Storage**: Vacuoles can store various substances, including nutrients, waste products, and ions. They help maintain the internal environment of the cell by sequestering harmful materials and storing useful ones for later use.\n\n2. **Waste Disposal**: Vacuoles can contain enzymes that break down cellular waste products, which helps keep the cell clean and free of debris.\n\n3. **Regulation of Osmotic Balance**: Vacuoles contribute to the regulation of the cell's osmotic balance by controlling the concentration of solutes and water within the cell. This helps maintain cell turgor and prevents it from bursting or shrinking due to osmotic pressure changes.\n\n4. **Endocytosis and Exocytosis**: Vacuoles are involved in the processes of endocytosis (intake of external substances) and exocytosis (expulsion of internal substances). They can form from the cell membrane to engulf external materials or fuse with the cell membrane to release contents outside the cell.\n\n5. **Isolation of Harmful Materials**: Vacuoles can isolate harmful substances, like toxins or pathogens, preventing them from damaging other parts of the cell.\n\nOverall, while vacuoles in animal cells are not as large or prominent as those in plant cells, they still play vital roles in maintaining cellular function and homeostasis.",
